@john_blues I should add my answer was for parallel.  Basically if they're at different voltages then the 'bigger' one will charge the 'smaller' one until the voltages equal each other.  When discharging & charging they'll do that as well, which may overstress the smaller one.

In serial is a bit different, but the voltage on the 'smaller' will drop faster (probably dropping below the safe voltage) while the bigger one is still forcing current thru it.  This is why dead battery packs (even back to the old NiCAD & NiMh ones) will have one dead cell, that's the weakest one failing first and killing the pack.  This is why LiPo packs have the balancing & protection circuits.

Finding matching cells is why those battery capacity testers are quite popular these days.
